class Solution:
    def resultingString(self, s: str) -> str:
        st = []
        for ch in s:
            st.append(ch)
            while len(st) >= 2:
                a, b = st[-2], st[-1]
                if (ord(a) - ord(b)) % 26 == 1 or (ord(b) - ord(a)) % 26 == 1:
                    st.pop()
                    st.pop()
                else:
                    break
        return ''.join(st)
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses a stack to simulate the removals in a single left-to-right pass. Whenever the top two characters are consecutive alphabetically (circularly), they are popped. This greedy approach is optimal because any later removals cannot affect earlier pairs once processed.

